bib_record.title: U-235 fission neutron spectrum averaged cross sections measured for some threshold reactions on Mg, Al, Ca, Sc, Ti, Fe, Co, Ni, Zn, Sr, Mo, Rh, In and Ce.

free_txt: Factors were applied to correct the measured count
rates for the following effects: sample size, cascade
gammas, attenuation within sample (Rh sample only),
Correlations between the results for the 34 reactions
are in the following matrix, which include covariances
in detection efficiencies and ratio measurements. The
order of the rows/columns corresponds to the order of
the subentries, with the monitor reaction first. The
matrix elements are given in percent.
Photo peak and total gamma detection efficiencies
determined using several IAEA standard gamma sources
at various counting distances. A 5mm thick acrylite
plate was attached to the detector front surfaces
during the measurements of the irradiated samples.
Heavy water thermal column with an enriched U-235
fission converter plate to produce a standard
fission neutron spectrum. The plate was disk shaped of
27 cm diam and 1.1 cm thickness, with a 1.95 g/cm2
layer of 90% enriched U-235 in the form of UO2-Al
cermet. A thermal neutron collimator which greatly
restricted the effective plate surface area was used
to reduce the perturbing effect of scattered neutrons
on the fission spectrum shape; as a result only a 3 cm
radius region remained for sample irradiation, the
fast flux at the plate surface being 10.**9 n/cm2/sec
The composition, purity and size of the samples are
given below. The powder and pebble samples were shaped
into thin discs and wrapped in polyethylene film.
Samples were irradiated for up to 74.5 hours attached
to the surface of the fission plate at a power level
of 5 MW. Six such irradiations were performed.
